  <Docs since="14">
    <summary>The SpellCheckerSession interface provides the per client functionality of SpellCheckerService.</summary>
    <remarks>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">The SpellCheckerSession interface provides the per client functionality of SpellCheckerService.


 <format type="text/html"><h3>Applications</h3></format><list type="bullet"><item><term> Properly set the <c><see cref="!:NoType:android/R$attr;Href=../../../../reference/android/R.attr.html#inputType" /></c> in your editable
 text views, so that the spell checker will have enough context to help the
 user in editing text in them.
 </term></item></list><format type="text/html"><h3>Security</h3></format><list type="bullet"><item><term>Only the system is allowed to directly access a spell checker framework's
 <c><see cref="T:Android.Service.Textservice.SpellCheckerService" /></c> interface, via the
 <c><see cref="!:NoType:android/Manifest$permission;Href=../../../../reference/android/Manifest.permission.html#BIND_TEXT_SERVICE" /></c> permission.  This is
 enforced in the system by not binding to a spell checker service that does
 not require this permission.

 </term></item><item><term>The user must explicitly enable a new spell checker in settings before
 they can be enabled, to confirm with the system that they know about it
 and want to make it available for use.
 </term></item></list></para>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">In most cases, applications that are using the standard
 <c><see cref="T:Android.Widget.TextView" /></c> or its subclasses will have little they need
 to do to work well with spell checker services.  The main things you need to
 be aware of are:</para>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">For the rare people amongst us writing client applications that use the spell checker service
 directly, you will need to use <c><see cref="M:Android.Views.TextService.SpellCheckerSession.GetSuggestions(Android.Views.TextService.TextInfo,System.Int32)" /></c> or
 <c><see cref="M:Android.Views.TextService.SpellCheckerSession.GetSuggestions(Android.Views.TextService.TextInfo[],System.Int32,System.Int32)" /></c> for obtaining results from the spell checker
 service by yourself.</para>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">There are a lot of security issues associated with spell checkers,
 since they could monitor all the text being sent to them
 through, for instance, <c><see cref="T:Android.Widget.TextView" /></c>.
 The Android spell checker framework also allows
 arbitrary third party spell checkers, so care must be taken to restrict their
 selection and interactions.</para>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">Here are some key points about the security architecture behind the
 spell checker framework:</para>
      <para tool="javadoc-to-mdoc">
        <format type="text/html">
          <a href="http://developer.android.com/reference/android/view/textservice/SpellCheckerSession.html" target="_blank">[Android Documentation]</a>
        </format>
      </para>
    </remarks>
    <since version="Added in API level 14" />
  </Docs>
